Westmark Loyalty Account Analysis

BYU-Idaho Westmark Project Team

The Data

# run profit calculation function on the data
Profit <- profit_calculation(history_2023, loyalty_2023, checking_2021)

normalized_profit <- normalize_profit(history_2023, Profit)

The following is an initial overview of the data provided by Westmark. In order to assure proper analysis and maintain sense of standardization, .csv file data as cleaned, values correct, and separated into properly updated variables.

Age Groups

The graph shows the number of accounts by age group, alongside the percentage of those with or without a Rewards account. Notable points:

  • The 18-29 age group is notably larger than any other age group within the data, containing roughly 1200 users.
  • Younger clients (ages < 30) are more likely to sign up for a Loyalty account, compared to their older counterparts.
  • As client’s age increases, the likelihood of having a loyalty account decreases exponentially.
Profit$Age_Group <- factor(
  Profit$Age_Group,
  levels = c("< 18" ,"18 - 29","30 - 39","40 - 49","50 - 59",
             "60 - 69","70 - 79","80 - 89"," > 90"  ))

ch_age <- Profit |> 
  group_by(Age_Group, Rewards) |> 
  filter(Age > 16 & Age < 100) |> 
  summarise(total = n()) |> 
  mutate(pct= prop.table(total) * 100)

# Graph.
ggplot(ch_age, aes(x = Age_Group, y = total, fill = Rewards)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label=paste0(sprintf("%1.1f", pct),"%")),
            position=position_stack(vjust=0.5), size = 4) +
  labs(title = "Age Groups and Account Type",
       x = "Age",
       y = "Total Accounts",
       fill = "Loyalty Account") +
  scale_fill_manual(labels=c("Yes", "No"), values=c("#cc4b56", "#5b6ebd")) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Branches

The following graph shows the number of accounts by Branch Number and Loyalty Account status. Notable Points:

  • The Loyalty account percentage ranges from 35% to 61% for all branches excluding those meant for online banking.
  • Branch 5 has the most customers within the data, and over half of them are Loyalty account holders.
  • Branches 3 and 16 have the highest percentage of Loyalty account clients.

products <- other_products %>% 
  mutate(CD = case_when(CD == 0 ~"No",CD >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         Auto = case_when(Auto == 0 ~"No",Auto >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         RealEstate = case_when(RealEstate == 0 ~"No",RealEstate >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         MoneyMarket = case_when(MoneyMarket == 0 ~"No",MoneyMarket >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         SecondarySaving = case_when(SecondarySaving == 0 ~"No",SecondarySaving >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         VEHL = case_when(VEHL == 0 ~"No",VEHL >= 1 ~ "Yes")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!ukey, names_to = "products") %>% 
  left_join(Profit, by = "ukey")

Other Products

The following graph shows the Other Products and the Reward status makeup per category. Notable points:

  • Most of the product types have an almost equal percentage distribution across the board, Money Market being the exception.
  • Money Market loan customers stand apart by having 12% Loyalty Account make up, as well as the least amount of customers.
  • Secondary Savings and Auto Loans are the most popular Other Products.

Income

Age Group

The following graph shows the amount of income brought in from total fees per customer by age group. Notable points:

  • Overall, Loyalty Account holders bring in more income than those with regular banking accounts.
  • Loyalty Accounts have a much wider range than Regular Accounts do.

Branches

The following graph compares income between branches and the type of account. Notable points:

  • The Loyalty Accounts for every branch retain a higher median than Regular Accounts.
  • The difference between the two groups is not universal.

Profit

Age Groups

Branches

Normalized Profit

In 2023, Westmark updated the time frame in which people can accumulate points, decreasing from three to two years. Because of this change in policy, we could see a lot of values in the data that were negatively affected. To normalize this, we calculated the amount of points they would’ve earned in the 2023 period and subtracted it from the amount of rewards people redeemed that year. The visuals below represent that adjustment:

  • We can see that the median spending for each age group is noticeably higher on the loyalty accounts, except for the 90+ age group.
  • The difference is increasingly noticeable in users from age 30-60.

Branches

We can see across the board that Loyalty Accounts have a higher median looking at each individual branch, with the exception of Branch 6. This is a positive sign as it shows that generally Loyalty Accounts bring in more profit.

Median Profit Comparison

The summary provided aids in visualizing the findings mentioned above.

datatable(normalized_profit %>%
  group_by(Age_Group, Rewards) %>%
  summarise(Median = round(median(normalized_profit),2)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Rewards, values_from = Median) %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list(Regular = 0, Loyalty = 0)) %>% 
  mutate(Difference = round(Loyalty - Regular,2)) %>% 
  inner_join(normalized_profit %>% group_by(Age_Group) %>% summarise(Count = n()), by = "Age_Group"))
datatable(normalized_profit %>%
  group_by(BranchNumber, Rewards) %>%
  summarise(Median = round(median(normalized_profit),2)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Rewards, values_from = Median) %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list(Regular = 0, Loyalty = 0)) %>% 
  mutate(Difference = round(Loyalty - Regular,2)) %>% 
  inner_join(normalized_profit %>% group_by(BranchNumber) %>% summarise(Count = n()), by = "BranchNumber"))

Mean Profit Differences

Upon comparing the means naturally, there’s a variance in the numbers shown. The biggest difference seems to be in the 18-29 age group, as they are largest group in the data. The assumption would be there are specific individuals or subgroups in that age group that are skewing the averages.

datatable(normalized_profit %>%
  group_by(Age_Group, Rewards) %>%
  summarise(Mean = round(mean(normalized_profit),2)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Rewards, values_from = Mean) %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list(Regular = 0, Loyalty = 0)) %>% 
  mutate(Difference = round(Loyalty - Regular,2)) %>% 
  inner_join(normalized_profit %>% group_by(Age_Group) %>% summarise(Count = n()), by = "Age_Group"))

Most of the branches below seem to show a positive difference, which again, is a good sign.

datatable(normalized_profit %>%
  group_by(BranchNumber, Rewards) %>%
  summarise(Mean = round(mean(normalized_profit),2)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Rewards, values_from = Mean) %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list(Regular = 0, Loyalty = 0)) %>% 
  mutate(Difference = round(Loyalty - Regular,2)) %>% 
  inner_join(normalized_profit %>% group_by(BranchNumber) %>% summarise(Count = n()), by = "BranchNumber"))

Other Products

Products and Profit

When we look at how the different loan types for the data, we can see that it’s generally in favor of the Loyalty Accounts in terms of profits, with the exception of CD loans.

products <- other_products %>% 
  mutate(CD = case_when(CD == 0 ~"No",CD >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         Auto = case_when(Auto == 0 ~"No",Auto >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         RealEstate = case_when(RealEstate == 0 ~"No",RealEstate >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         MoneyMarket = case_when(MoneyMarket == 0 ~"No",MoneyMarket >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         SecondarySaving = case_when(SecondarySaving == 0 ~"No",SecondarySaving >= 1 ~ "Yes"),
         VEHL = case_when(VEHL == 0 ~"No",VEHL >= 1 ~ "Yes")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!ukey, names_to = "products") %>% 
  left_join(normalized_profit, by = "ukey") %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  filter(value == "Yes")

# Graph.
ggplot(products)+
  aes(x = Rewards, y = normalized_profit, fill = Rewards)+
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_manual(labels=c("Yes", "No"), values=c("#cc4b56", "#5b6ebd")) +
  facet_wrap(~products)+
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Products by Rewards Type", x = "Products", y = "Normalized Profit", fill = "Rewards") +
  theme_bw() + 
   scale_y_continuous(limit = c(-50, 300), labels=scales::dollar_format())
